      <!-- Explainer guide -->
      <div class="states-guide">
        <h2>How State Income Tax Works</h2>
        <p>Most U.S. residents owe two separate income taxes: a <strong>federal income tax</strong> (paid to the IRS) and a <strong>state income tax</strong> (paid to the state where you live and work). Federal tax applies to all U.S. residents regardless of state — the brackets and rates are identical whether you live in California or Texas. State income tax is a separate obligation with its own brackets, deductions, and filing requirements that vary significantly from state to state.</p>
        <p>Each state calculator on this site shows both taxes side by side: your estimated federal income tax from the 2025 IRS brackets, and your estimated state income tax using your state's published rates and brackets.</p>
        <h2 style="margin-top:22px">Graduated vs. Flat Rate States</h2>
        <p>States that have income tax generally fall into two categories:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Graduated rate states</strong> work like the federal system — lower income is taxed at lower rates, higher income at higher rates. Only the income within each bracket pays that bracket's rate. California, New York, Minnesota, and Oregon all use graduated systems.</li>
          <li><strong>Flat rate states</strong> apply a single percentage to all taxable income regardless of how much you earn. Illinois (4.95%), Pennsylvania (3.07%), and Arizona (2.50%) are examples. Flat states are simpler to calculate but don't offer the lower rates at the bottom that graduated states do.</li>
        </ul>
        <h2 style="margin-top:22px">States with No Income Tax</h2>
        <p>Nine states — Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, and Wyoming — impose no broad-based personal income tax on wages and salaries. This doesn't mean residents pay no taxes at all: these states typically have higher property taxes, sales taxes, or other revenue mechanisms. And federal income tax applies to all residents of all states without exception.</p>
        <p>Use the <a href="/income-tax-calculator">federal income tax calculator</a> to estimate your IRS tax regardless of your state, and select your state above for a combined federal + state estimate.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="states-faq">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions — State Income Taxes</h2>
        <div class="faq-accordion">

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              Do I have to pay state income tax if I live in a no-tax state?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>No. If you are a full-year resident of Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, or Wyoming, you owe no state income tax on wages or salary. You still owe federal income tax to the IRS — that obligation applies to all U.S. residents regardless of which state they live in.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              Which state has the highest income tax rate?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>California has the highest top marginal state income tax rate at 13.3%, which applies to taxable income over $1 million for single filers. The next highest are Hawaii (11%), New Jersey (10.75%), Washington D.C. (10.75%), New York (10.9%), and Oregon (9.9%). However, these top rates only apply to high earners — most California residents pay an effective state rate well below 13.3%.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              What if I live in one state and work in another?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>If you live in one state and work in another, you may owe taxes in both — but most states have reciprocity agreements with neighboring states that let you pay tax only to your home state. If no reciprocity agreement exists, you typically pay income tax to the state where the work is performed, then claim a credit on your home state return for taxes paid to the other state, so you generally are not taxed twice on the same income. The rules vary by state — consult a tax professional if you are in this situation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              How is state income tax different from federal income tax?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>Federal income tax is collected by the IRS under a single uniform rate schedule that applies to all U.S. residents. State income tax is collected by your state's department of revenue under that state's own rules — different brackets, different deductions, different credits, and a separate return. You file Form 1040 for federal taxes and a separate state form for state taxes (if your state has an income tax). The two are calculated independently, though your state return often starts from your federal adjusted gross income as a baseline.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              How accurate are these state tax estimates?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>These are planning estimates based on each state's published income tax brackets. They do not account for all state-specific deductions, exemptions, credits, local income taxes (like New York City's), or special situations. The federal estimate uses the 2025 IRS tax brackets. For a final, accurate tax calculation, use your state's official tax forms or consult a qualified tax professional. These calculators are designed to give you a reliable ballpark — not to replace a filed return.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              Does moving to a no-tax state actually save money?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>It can — but the full picture includes all taxes, not just income tax. States with no income tax often compensate through higher property taxes, sales taxes, or other fees. Texas has no income tax but some of the highest property tax rates in the country. New Hampshire has no income or sales tax but relatively high property taxes. The net benefit of moving depends heavily on your income level, home ownership status, and spending patterns. High-income earners moving from California (13.3% top rate) to Texas (0%) tend to see the largest savings. Lower-income households may see smaller differences once all taxes are considered.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-acc-item">
            <button class="faq-acc-btn">
              When is state income tax due?
              <span class="faq-acc-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-acc-answer">
              <p>Most states follow the federal deadline and require state returns to be filed by April 15. Some states have slightly different deadlines. If you file a federal extension (Form 4868), most states automatically grant a matching extension for filing — but not for payment. If you owe state tax, payment is generally still due by the original April deadline even if your filing is extended. Check your state's department of revenue for the exact rules.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

